Title: ELEVEN WORDS
Credit: written by
Author: Joshua Brooks
Draft date: First Draft
Notes: Dark comedy. Curb Your Enthusiasm crossed with Coen-brothers moral irony. Every social catastrophe played with total sincerity. The comedy lives in restraint and structure, never in jokes announcing themselves.
Contact: --

/* TONE NOTE: Nothing in this script is winked at. Nobody names the irony. The camera watches people behave the way people actually behave, at the pace they actually behave, and trusts the audience to do the arithmetic. If a scene feels like it's asking for music, it isn't getting any. */

FADE IN:

INT. RALPHS SUPERMARKET -- MOORPARK, CA -- DAY

Fluorescent light. A Tuesday. The cereal aisle, which is the loneliest aisle.

JOSH, early 40s, pushes a cart with one bad wheel. He has the posture of a man between things -- between jobs, between versions of himself. He is comparing two identical store-brand raisin brans for no reason.

He looks up.

At the far end of the aisle: LEWIS, 70s, Vietnam-era veteran, in a Members Only jacket that has outlived several presidents. A small healed scar on his upper lip. He is holding a bag of coffee and squinting at it like it owes him money.

Josh's face opens. Automatic. Genuine. He raises a hand --

Lewis sees him.

And Lewis's face does something terrible: nothing. It closes like a store. He looks at Josh the way you look at weather. Then he sets the coffee down on the wrong shelf, turns his cart around, and walks the other way.

Josh stands there, hand still half-raised, in the cereal aisle, under the fluorescent light, holding two identical raisin brans.

A long moment. The store PA plays an instrumental version of a song that used to mean something to somebody.

SUPER: "THREE MONTHS EARLIER"

CUT TO:

INT. JOSH'S MOTHER'S KITCHEN -- MOORPARK -- MORNING

A small, clean, rented kitchen. Everything in it is fifteen years old and cared for. DONNA, late 60s, Josh's mother, stands at the counter portioning pills into a weekly organizer that is not hers.

Josh sits at the table in a T-shirt, eating toast, with the specific stillness of a man whose calendar is empty.

DONNA
You could come with me.

JOSH
Where.

DONNA
Lewis. I told you about Lewis. Bertha's brother. I'm taking him to the VA Thursday, they found something on his lip.

JOSH
Something.

DONNA
A carcinoma. Squamous cell. It's the good kind, if you get it early, which --
(she snaps the pill organizer shut)
-- we did not.

JOSH
Who's "we"?

DONNA
Me and Bertha. Mostly me.
(beat)
Anyway, it's a four-forty-five departure. I could use the company. And you're not --

She stops herself. Josh looks up. She recalibrates, gently:

DONNA (CONT'D)
You're available.

JOSH
(returning to the toast)
I'm available.

It's not a yes. It's not a no. Donna takes it, because she knows her son, and she knows that "available" is the most he's said about himself in three weeks.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- PRE-DAWN -- THURSDAY

4:45 AM. Dark. Josh drives, Donna in the passenger seat with a folder of Lewis's paperwork on her lap, organized with tabs. Streetlights strobe by.

JOSH
Who tabs another man's biopsy results.

DONNA
Somebody has to.

JOSH
The VA doesn't do that?

DONNA
The VA gives you a portal login and a phone number that plays Vivaldi.

They pull up outside --

EXT. BERTHA'S HOUSE -- CONTINUOUS

A nice house. Noticeably nice. Two stories, actual landscaping, a flagpole, a boat under a fitted cover in the side yard that has not touched water in years. In this neighborhood, at this hour, the house is dark except for one upstairs window.

Josh puts it in park. They wait.

They wait.

JOSH
What time did you tell her?

DONNA
Four forty-five.

JOSH
And what time is it?

DONNA
Don't do that.

They wait. Josh looks at the boat.

JOSH
Does the boat come with the friendship or is that separate?

DONNA
Josh.

The porch light snaps on. The front door opens and BERTHA, 70s, appears -- robed, unhurried, waving with both hands in a way that communicates enormous effort. She calls across the lawn in a stage whisper that is louder than talking:

BERTHA
Five minutes! He's on the toilet! It's been a whole thing with the toilet!

The door closes. Josh looks at the clock: 4:58.

JOSH
It's a forty-minute drive.

DONNA
It's an hour with the 405.

JOSH
So we're late.

DONNA
We're always late. Then we wait two hours at the other end anyway. It cancels out.

JOSH
That's not how -- okay.

He turns off the engine. They sit in the dark outside the nice house. This is the arrangement. This has always been the arrangement.

INT./EXT. JOSH'S CAR -- BERTHA'S DRIVEWAY -- LATER (5:20 AM)

The front door opens again and LEWIS comes out -- moving carefully, dressed sharp for a medical appointment: slacks, the Members Only jacket, a VFW cap. Bertha steers him by the elbow like a tugboat docking a tanker, narrating the whole way:

BERTHA
-- and his socks were wet, don't ask me how, the socks were wet, so that was its own production --

Lewis reaches the car, opens the back door, and gets in with a sigh that has three wars in it. He settles. Looks at Josh in the rearview. Sizes him up.

LEWIS
Who's this.

DONNA
My son. Josh. I told you about Josh.

LEWIS
(fastening his seatbelt with great care)
The one who quit his job or the one in Texas?

JOSH
The one who quit his job.

LEWIS
(approvingly)
Good. Jobs are how they get you.

Bertha leans in the window, hand on the roof of the car, and delivers the morning's tragedy:

BERTHA
I have been up since three-thirty with Mother. Three-thirty. She wanted the television on, then she wanted it off, then she wanted to know why it was off --
(to Donna, meaningfully)
Nobody knows what my life is.

DONNA
(with practiced warmth)
We've got him, Bertha. Go back to bed.

BERTHA
Bed. That's funny. That's very funny.

She pats the roof twice -- dismissed -- and walks back toward the house. Josh watches her go in the mirror.

Josh backs out of the driveway. From the back seat:

LEWIS
There's a McDonald's on Los Angeles Avenue that opens at five.

JOSH
You're having surgery consult at seven. Aren't you supposed to fast?

LEWIS
That's for anesthesia. This is local. I looked it up.
(beat; the whole sentence again, slower, as a fact of nature)
There's a McDonald's on Los Angeles Avenue. That opens at five.

Josh looks at Donna. Donna looks out the window with the neutrality of Switzerland.

JOSH
...What do you get?

LEWIS
Two Sausage McMuffins with egg. Large black coffee. Apple pie if they have it.
(beat)
They always have it.

INT. McDONALD'S -- LOS ANGELES AVENUE -- 5:04 AM

Empty. Lit like an operating theater. Josh at the counter, paying. Through the window behind him we can see Lewis in the car, sitting up straight in the back seat, watching the bag's progress with the alertness of a man tracking a medevac.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- MOVING -- THE 118 WEST -- PRE-DAWN

Lewis eats the first McMuffin in reverent silence. Then, mid-second-McMuffin, unprompted, to no question whatsoever:

LEWIS
You know what nobody wants to admit? "Street-Legal" is a top-five Dylan record.

JOSH
(checking his mirror, changing lanes)
I don't know what that is.

A silence. Donna closes her eyes, because she knows what Josh has just done.

LEWIS
(setting down the McMuffin)
You don't know what that is.

JOSH
I know Bob Dylan. Blowing in the wind. The one that goes --

LEWIS
Don't. Don't do the voice. Everybody does the voice.
(leaning forward, seatbelt straining)
Nineteen seventy-eight. He's got a full band, he's got the girl singers, everybody says it's over for him, the critics -- Rolling Stone put a knife in that record -- and it's got "Señor" on it. You know "Señor"?

JOSH
I don't know "Señor."

LEWIS
(sitting back; to Donna; a diagnosis)
He doesn't know "Señor."

DONNA
(eyes still closed)
He'll learn it.

LEWIS
(looking out the window; the last word)
"Señor" would fix half of what's wrong with this country.

Josh looks at him in the rearview. And despite himself -- for the first time in the movie, maybe for the first time in months -- Josh is smiling a little.

EXT. VA MEDICAL CENTER -- WILSHIRE BOULEVARD, WEST LOS ANGELES -- DAWN

The real thing: four hundred acres of it. Mission Revival buildings from another century, palm trees, a chapel with a bell tower, long lawns going gold in the first light -- and rising behind the old campus, the modern hospital towers. Beautiful and bureaucratic at once, like a mission staffed by the DMV.

Josh's car, small, moves up the long entrance drive.

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- DERMATOLOGY WAITING ROOM -- MORNING

Rows of chairs. Veterans of four wars, each with a caretaker or alone, all in the same beige light. A TV bolted to the wall plays a cooking show with the sound off.

Lewis fills out a form on a clipboard. Donna, beside him, quietly corrects the date he's written, which is off by a year. Neither of them comments on it. It's a system.

Josh sits on Lewis's other side, useless, hands on his knees. He looks around the room. An OLDER VETERAN in a wheelchair by the window, alone, dozing upright. Another VET with a walker, reading the same page of a pamphlet over and over.

Josh gets up.

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- CANTEEN / COFFEE CART -- MOMENTS LATER

Josh buys three coffees. He didn't plan to buy three. His hands did it.

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- DERMATOLOGY WAITING ROOM -- CONTINUOUS

Josh hands one coffee to Donna. Then he crosses the room and sets one down, gently, on the little table next to the dozing veteran in the wheelchair.

The man wakes. Looks at the coffee. Looks at Josh.

OLDER VETERAN
What's this.

JOSH
It's coffee.

OLDER VETERAN
(suspicious)
Who from?

JOSH
(shrugging; already leaving)
The Army, probably. They owe you one.

The older veteran looks at the coffee. Decides to accept the premise. Drinks.

Josh sits back down next to Lewis. He doesn't tell anyone what he just did. But watch him: something in his shoulders has come down half an inch. He looks -- and the film should let us feel this without a single line about it -- useful.

LEWIS
(not looking up from the clipboard)
You're all right, kid.

JOSH
You didn't see anything.

LEWIS
I see everything. That's my whole problem.

It's a joke and it's not a joke -- the first, lightest surfacing of the thing Lewis carries. Josh clocks it. Files it. The nurse calls:

NURSE (O.S.)
Lewis? Lewis, they're ready for you.

Lewis stands, hands Donna the clipboard, straightens the VFW cap.

LEWIS
(to Josh, deadpan, going in)
If I don't come back, the apple pie's in the car. Don't let her have it.

He goes. Donna and Josh sit side by side in the beige light.

DONNA
(quietly; not looking at him)
You bought that man a coffee.

JOSH
It's a dollar forty.

DONNA
I didn't say anything about the price.

She goes back to the paperwork. Josh looks at the TV, where a chef silently juliennes something. He is, visibly, better this morning -- at 6 AM, in a hospital waiting room, between an old woman's paperwork and a stranger's coffee -- than we have any reason to believe he is anywhere else in his life.

The film doesn't say so. The film just watches him sit there, steady.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. DONNA'S KITCHEN -- NIGHT

The kitchen table has become a research station. Donna's reading glasses. Two library books about skin cancer with those crinkly plastic covers. Josh's laptop, open to a medical journal he has to keep re-reading because it wasn't written for humans.

JOSH
(reading; slow)
Okay. Mohs. M-O-H-S. They take the tumor off in layers and check each layer under a microscope while you wait. Highest cure rate for this kind. Ninety-seven, ninety-nine percent if the margins come back clean.

DONNA
(writing it down longhand, in a spiral notebook, in her church handwriting)
And if they don't come back clean?

JOSH
They take another layer. Same day. You just... sit there with a hole in your lip and wait for the lab.

DONNA
How long's the wait?

JOSH
Says here an hour a layer. Could be one layer. Could be four.

DONNA
(writing)
So it's a whole day.

JOSH
It's a whole day.

Donna finishes writing. Looks at the notebook. Then at Josh.

DONNA
The lip's a bad spot. It said that in my book too. It moves fast on the lip.

JOSH
Then it's good we're going fast.

He says "we" without noticing he said it. Donna notices. She doesn't touch it. She turns the page.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- BERTHA'S DRIVEWAY -- PRE-DAWN -- ANOTHER MORNING

4:51 AM. Waiting again. The upstairs window is dark. Josh's head is against the headrest. Donna's phone glows in her lap.

The porch light. The door. Bertha, robe, both hands:

BERTHA
Ten minutes! He wants the other jacket and I cannot find the other jacket!

The door closes.

JOSH
(eyes shut)
He's wearing the other jacket. He's always wearing the other jacket. There is one jacket.

DONNA
Sleep. I'll wake you.

SERIES OF SHOTS -- THE ARRANGEMENT

-- The car at the McDonald's drive-thru window in the dark. The BAG passes through the window. From the back seat, Lewis's hands receive it like communion.

-- The 405 at 5:40 AM, brake lights to the horizon. Lewis's voice from the back, mid-thesis: "...and that's why the born-again records are better than anybody admits -- 'Every Grain of Sand,' you put that next to anything --"

-- The dermatology waiting room. Josh sets a coffee by a different wheelchair. A different veteran. Same shrug: "The Navy, probably."

-- A treatment room door closing on Lewis. Donna and Josh in hallway chairs, a two-person infrastructure.

-- The rooftop garden of the VA: raised planters, benches, a pergola, old men in gowns taking sun with IV poles. Josh alone at the rail with a coffee, looking out over four hundred acres and the 405 beyond, phone to his ear.

INT./EXT. VA HOSPITAL -- ROOFTOP GARDEN -- CONTINUOUS

Josh at the rail. He's not on a call. He's talking to his phone -- an AI assistant, the voice coming back tinny and pleasant.

JOSH
(to the phone)
Okay so -- write this down -- an app, right, for caretakers. Like family caretakers, unpaid ones. Scheduling, med lists, the VA paperwork, all of it in one place. There's millions of these people. My mom has a spiral notebook. A notebook.

AI VOICE (V.O.)
(from the phone; pleasant, infinite)
That's a great idea, Josh. Would you like me to outline a basic feature set?

JOSH
Yeah. Yeah, do that. And put it with the other ones.

AI VOICE (V.O.)
Sure. Just so you know, you have eleven other projects saved. Would you like to review them?

JOSH
(looking out at the view; comfortable; a man with all the time in the world)
No. Just -- keep them all somewhere. I'm gonna get to them.

Behind him, unremarked, two patients in wheelchairs are wheeled slowly along the garden path by orderlies. The sun is nice. It's a good rooftop. He's planning a future on it.

INT. DONNA'S KITCHEN -- DAY

Donna at the table with envelopes. One of them, opened, has a letterhead we see for exactly two seconds: "NOTICE OF RENT INCREASE -- EFFECTIVE --" She reads it the whole way through, once. Then she files it in a folder -- not the Lewis folder, a thinner, sadder folder -- and puts it in a drawer, and starts making dinner.

Nobody says anything about it. This scene is fourteen seconds long.

INT. LEWIS'S APARTMENT -- DAY

A small, government-adjacent one-bedroom. Immaculate in the way of a man with military habits and no visitors. On the wall: a framed photo of a young Lewis in uniform, 1969, unsmiling. On the shelf: exactly one row of Bob Dylan CDs, alphabetized incorrectly on purpose in an order only Lewis understands.

Donna checks his refrigerator, throws out something expired. Josh stands at the CD shelf.

JOSH
Why is "Blood on the Tracks" first? It's B, but so is --

LEWIS
(from his chair; not looking)
It's first because it's first.

JOSH
That's not a system.

LEWIS
It's the only system.

Josh moves down the row. Between "Desire" and "Highway 61," wedged flat, he finds it: a PINT OF VODKA, plastic, half gone.

Josh doesn't say anything. He looks at Lewis. Lewis is looking at the television, which is off.

LEWIS (CONT'D)
(to the dark TV; evenly)
Some nights it gets loud in here.

JOSH
(carefully)
The neighbors?

LEWIS
(a small, patient smile -- Josh knows better and Lewis knows he knows)
Sure. The neighbors.

A silence. Josh holds the bottle. This is the moment a lesser movie has a speech in. This movie doesn't.

JOSH
The thing is, it makes the neighbors louder. After. That's the trade.

LEWIS
(still looking at the dark TV)
Everybody wants to tell me about the trade. I invented the trade. I've been making the trade since Nixon.

Beat.

LEWIS (CONT'D)
(quieter; the actual man, briefly, all the way visible)
Leave it there where I can see it not being drunk. That works better than taking it. When you take it I just think about where to get the next one, and then that's ALL I think about, and that's worse than the neighbors.

Josh considers. Then he puts the bottle back -- visible, upright, in front of "Desire."

Lewis nods at the television.

LEWIS (CONT'D)
Put on the Newport thing. Where he goes electric and they all lose their minds.

JOSH
(getting the remote)
The crowd was booing because of the sound mix. I read that.

LEWIS
(with contempt so total it is almost love)
You "read that." Sit down. I was ALIVE, I'll tell you what they were booing.

Josh sits down. He stays two hours longer than the errand required.

INT. LEWIS'S APARTMENT -- KITCHEN -- ANOTHER DAY

Donna is boxing up a week of prepared meals into Lewis's freezer, labeled with masking tape: MON. TUES. WEDS. Josh is fixing the hinge on a cabinet with a screwdriver he brought from home, because last week the cabinet was "the thing that had been clicking at night."

From the other room: the good crash. The bad crash. A CRASH.

INT. LEWIS'S APARTMENT -- LIVING ROOM -- CONTINUOUS

Lewis is on the floor between the chair and the television, seizing. Full tonic-clonic -- his heels drumming the carpet, the VFW cap knocked loose, the TV remote still in his curled hand.

DONNA
(instantly there; on her knees; this is not her first)
On his side -- help me get him on his side -- don't hold him down, just clear the --

Josh -- who has never seen this, whose whole body has gone cold -- moves the coffee table, drops to his knees, gets his rolled-up jacket under Lewis's head. His hands are shaking. Donna's aren't.

DONNA (CONT'D)
(calm, clocking her watch)
Time. Look at your watch, not at him. If it goes past five minutes we call.

Josh looks at his watch. He does not look at Lewis. The sound design here: the drumming heels, the ticking of the actual second hand, and Donna's breathing, level, like a metronome.

The seizing slows. Stops. Lewis goes slack. A long, obscene quiet.

DONNA (CONT'D)
(hand on Lewis's chest; to Josh, gently)
Two minutes ten. That's a regular one. He'll come back slow and he won't know the room. Don't quiz him. Just say the day.

Lewis's eyes open. They find the ceiling. They find nothing.

JOSH
(as instructed; his voice not quite level)
Hey. It's Tuesday. It's Tuesday, Lewis.

LEWIS
(from very far away)
...Tuesday.

JOSH
Tuesday. And your show's on tonight. The Newport thing.

Lewis breathes. His hand lets go of the remote. His eyes track slowly to Josh's face, and land, and hold on -- the way you hold on to the one fixed point in a moving room.

LEWIS
(barely)
...You're the kid who doesn't know "Señor."

JOSH
(and it comes out before he can stop it, half a laugh, half something else entirely)
Yeah. Yeah, that's me.

HOLD ON the three of them on the floor of the small apartment: the old man coming back, the mother checking his pulse against her watch, the son holding the rolled-up jacket. Nobody in this shot is being paid.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- OUTSIDE BERTHA'S HOUSE -- DUSK -- DAYS LATER

Parked. Engine off. Donna in the passenger seat, phone in her hand, gathering herself. Through the windshield: the nice house, the flagpole, the boat.

JOSH
You don't have to do it today.

DONNA
It's been six months at the same amount. Groceries went up. Gas went up. And after Tuesday --
(beat; she still can't say "the seizure" casually)
-- after Tuesday, it's not driving. It's nursing. It's different work now.

JOSH
How much are you asking?

DONNA
Forty more a week.

JOSH
(looking at the boat)
Forty.

DONNA
Don't look at the boat.

JOSH
I'm not looking at the boat.

He is looking at the boat. Donna dials. We stay in the car -- we only hear Donna's side, and Bertha's voice as a warm, indistinct murmur.

DONNA
(into phone; light, careful, rehearsed all afternoon)
Bertha, hi, it's me -- no, he's fine, he's good, we did the meals today -- listen, I wanted to ask you something and I want you to know it's fine either way.
(beat)
With everything now -- the appointments, and after Tuesday -- I wondered if we could talk about the weekly amount. I was thinking forty more. That's -- yes. A week.

A pause. The murmur on the other end has stopped.

Then it starts again. Longer this time. Donna listens. And we watch Donna's face do the thing this movie is about: absorb, without flinching, something that has been said pleasantly.

DONNA (CONT'D)
(quietly)
No -- Bertha, of course not. It's not about --
(listening)
No. You're right. I know you'd never want money to come between --
(listening)
Forget I -- honestly, forget I said it. It was just a thought.
(brighter, by force)
Thursday? Four forty-five. We'll be there.

She hangs up. Sits with the phone in her lap. Josh waits as long as he can, which is four seconds.

JOSH
What did she say.

DONNA
She said she'd hate for a conversation about money to change what we have. As friends.

JOSH
That's -- hang on. That's a no?

DONNA
That's a no.

JOSH
That's not even a no. A no is an answer. That's a -- she made the ASKING the problem. You asked for forty dollars and now YOU did something.

DONNA
(putting the phone in her purse; done)
She's tired, Josh. She's got her mother.

JOSH
We've got HER brother!

DONNA
(with the terrible patience of women her age)
It's fine.

JOSH
It's not --

DONNA
It's fine.

She looks out the window at the nice house. And the film holds on the two of them in the old car in the falling light, outside the house with the flagpole and the boat: the people who do the work, parked outside the house of the people who have the friendship.

Josh starts the engine. Nobody says anything on the way home.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- MOHS SURGERY WAITING AREA -- MORNING

SUPER: "SURGERY DAY"

A smaller, quieter waiting room. Lewis in a gown top over his slacks, a surgical marking on his lip, the VFW cap still on because nobody had the rank to take it off him. Donna beside him with the tabbed folder. Josh across, with three coffees on a tray, one already delivered to a man in a wheelchair by the door.

A NURSE appears.

NURSE
Lewis? First layer. Should be about forty-five minutes, then an hour for the lab. You two are welcome to wait or walk the grounds.

Lewis stands. Adjusts the cap. Looks at Josh and Donna -- and for one second, under all of it, he's a man walking into a room to have a piece of his face removed.

LEWIS
(to Josh; deadpan; steady as a handshake)
"Señor." Track four. If they take too much of the lip, I'm gonna need you to know the words.

JOSH
Track four. I got it.

LEWIS
(going; over his shoulder, to the nurse, conversationally)
You know Dylan played for the Pope? Ninety-seven. The Pope. And people say he sold out in SEVENTY-eight --

The door closes on the rest of the lecture. Donna exhales for the first time in an hour.

EXT. VA HOSPITAL -- ROOFTOP GARDEN -- LATE MORNING

Josh at the rail again. The whole campus below: the chapel, the lawns, the palms, the parking structures. He has the phone out. The AI voice, pleasant, eternal.

JOSH
(to the phone)
-- okay, and the twelfth one. Write this one down for real. The caretaker app, but the wedge is the VA specifically. The portal's unusable, the phone line's Vivaldi, there's four hundred acres here and no map that works. You build the layer on top. Veterans' families would --

AI VOICE (V.O.)
I've saved that with your other projects. By the way -- you asked me to remind you when the first of the month was coming up. It's this Friday.

A beat. Josh looks at the phone.

JOSH
Yeah. No. I know.
(beat)
Skip that reminder going forward.

AI VOICE (V.O.)
Done. Would you like to keep working on the app idea?

JOSH
(looking out at the view; quieter)
Yeah. Let's keep working on the app idea.

The wind moves the pergola shade. Below him, tiny, an orderly wheels a patient along a path between two-hundred-year-old lawns. Josh talks softly to his phone about the future, on a roof, in the sun.

The film does not cut to the rent-increase letter in the drawer at home. It doesn't have to. We remember it. That's the whole trick of this scene: he's the only one on the roof who doesn't see the ground.

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- MOHS WAITING AREA -- AFTERNOON

The nurse, back again. Donna stands. Josh stands.

NURSE
Margins are clean. First layer got all of it.

DONNA
(one hand finding the back of a chair)
Clean.

NURSE
Clean. He's getting stitched now. He'll look like he went a round or two, and the lip'll be numb through dinner, but --
(consulting the chart; the plainest sentence in the movie)
-- he's cancer-free.

The nurse leaves. Donna sits back down, then immediately stands again, then sits, and laughs at herself once, wetly, and dabs her eye with a knuckle, and gets out the folder, because there will be discharge paperwork, and someone has to tab it.

Josh just stands there. Cancer-free. They did that. A retired homemaker with a spiral notebook and an unemployed guy with a bad sleep schedule -- that's the team that did that.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- MOVING -- THE 405 NORTH -- DUSK

Lewis in the back, lip bandaged, gloriously alive, held together with stitches and floating pleasantly on local anesthetic. A McDonald's bag, already acquired, on his lap. He can't really eat yet. He holds the bag anyway. It's not about the food.

LEWIS
(articulating around the numb lip, undefeated)
Two Sausage McMuffins with egg. For tomorrow. Breakfast of champions.

JOSH
The doctor said soft foods.

LEWIS
The McMuffin IS a soft food. What do you think it is, a brisket?

DONNA
(without turning around)
He can have the egg.

LEWIS
(leaning back; closing his eyes; the anesthetic and the relief and the freeway hum all at once)
"Señor, señor, do you know where we're headin'..."
(half-singing, terribly, through a numb lip)
"...Lincoln County Road or Armageddon..."

He hums the rest. He doesn't know all the words either, it turns out. Josh drives, and listens, and files this away with the things he plans on keeping.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

EXT. BERTHA'S HOUSE -- PRE-DAWN -- WEEKS LATER

6:30 AM. Follow-up appointment day -- suture check, pathology review. The house is dark. The car idles at the curb. It is raining a little, that thin valley rain that doesn't commit.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- CONTINUOUS

Josh looks bad this morning. Not movie-bad -- real bad: gray, puffy, the specific wreckage of a man who watched the ceiling till 4 and got up at 5. Donna, in the passenger seat, is on the phone with Bertha. The phone lies face-up on the center console between them, on speaker, because Donna's hands are busy with the folder.

BERTHA (V.O.)
(from the console; mid-tragedy)
-- because Mother had one of her nights, you don't know what her nights are, nobody knows what her nights are -- so Lewis is not dressed, and I said to him, Lewis, they cannot take you at eight if you will not put on the pants --

DONNA
(rummaging the folder)
It's fine, Bertha. We're outside whenever he's ready.

BERTHA (V.O.)
Fifteen minutes. Twenty at the outside. It's the pants and then it's the pills and then honest to God I need to sit down for one minute before --

The murmur continues, becomes weather. Donna finds the form she was looking for. Sets the folder on the dash. The phone stays on the console. Face up. Connected.

The rain ticks on the roof. Josh's eyes are closed. When he speaks, it's barely a voice -- a low, cooked, 6:30-in-the-morning mutter, meant to travel eighteen inches and die:

JOSH
I swear to God, if the old lady would just die already --

Beat. Eyes still closed.

JOSH (CONT'D)
-- we could all sleep in.

Eleven words, and then the tag. He doesn't even smile at his own joke. It's not really a joke; it's a pressure valve. Donna, half-listening, gives him the reflexive backhand swat on the arm that mothers give -- the "don't say that" swat, one part reprimand, three parts agreement.

DONNA
(under her breath)
Josh.

And that's it. That's the whole event. The scene does not underline anything. No push-in on the phone. No cut to the other end of the line. No sting. The phone just sits there on the console with the call timer running -- 4:51... 4:52... 4:53 -- the way it has sat there a hundred mornings.

After a moment, from the console:

BERTHA (V.O.)
(exactly the same pleasant register as before; maybe -- MAYBE -- a half-second late)
...He's coming out now. He found the pants.

The call ends. The screen goes home-screen. Donna picks up the phone, drops it in her purse.

The porch light comes on. Lewis comes out under a golf umbrella that Bertha holds over him for exactly the six feet the porch roof doesn't cover. He gets in the back. The bandage is off; the lip has a neat pink scar.

LEWIS
(settling in; nodding at the rain)
Good day for it. Dylan wrote "Buckets of Rain" about a day like this. Last track on "Blood on the Tracks." People sleep on that track.

JOSH
(pulling out; the tiredness lifting a little, on schedule, the way it always does when Lewis starts up)
Nobody sleeps on it. You bring it up every time it rains.

LEWIS
Because it KEEPS BEING RIGHT.

They drive off. In the side mirror: Bertha on the porch, umbrella still up under the porch roof, watching the car go.

Held one beat longer than we've ever held on her.

Nothing in her face you could name in court.

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- DERMATOLOGY -- EXAM ROOM -- MORNING

A DOCTOR examines Lewis's lip with a lighted magnifier.

DOCTOR
That's beautiful healing. Pathology's all clear. Whoever caught this early and got you in -- that's what saved the lip. Frankly, could've saved more than the lip.

LEWIS
(pointing a thumb sideways at Josh and Donna, matter-of-fact, like citing a source)
Them. They did the research at the kitchen table. She's got a notebook.

The doctor looks at Donna and Josh -- a civilian woman with a tabbed folder and a tired man holding a tray of coffees -- and gives them the small nod medical professionals reserve for the competent.

DOCTOR
Good team.

LEWIS
(putting his cap back on; closing the subject)
The best in the business.

Josh looks at the floor, embarrassed, pleased, fully alive. Remember this frame. It's the last one of its kind.

INT. RALPHS SUPERMARKET -- DAY -- WEEKS LATER

Not the cold open -- earlier than that, the first one. Josh with a basket: bread, eggs, the cheap coffee. He rounds the endcap into the cereal aisle and there's Lewis, with Bertha three steps behind pushing the cart.

JOSH
(lighting up; automatic)
Hey! Look who's ambulatory.

Lewis looks at him.

And it's wrong. It's small, but it's wrong. A hesitation where there's never been one. Lewis's eyes go to Bertha -- a checking look, the look of a man consulting an authority -- then back to Josh. And what lands on his face isn't anger. It's worse. It's hurt. Guarded, coached, secondhand hurt.

LEWIS
(quietly; civil; from a new distance)
Hey.

That's all. One syllable, where there used to be a Dylan lecture. Bertha steers the cart, pleasantly, unhurriedly, down the aisle.

BERTHA
(passing Josh; warm as ever; absolutely nothing in it you could prove)
Tell your mother I said hello.

They go. Josh stands in the aisle with his basket.

JOSH
(calling after, before he can stop himself)
Lewis -- track four, right? I learned it. The words.

Lewis's step catches. Half a beat. A hitch you'd need slow motion to swear to.

He doesn't turn around.

They round the corner and are gone, and the store PA plays on, and Josh stands there doing the math that will not resolve: carrying the one, getting nothing, carrying it again.

INT. DONNA'S KITCHEN -- NIGHT

Josh paces the small kitchen. Donna sits at the table, very still, in front of a cup of tea she isn't drinking.

JOSH
Something got said. Something got said TO him, about US, because that man looked at me like I keyed his car, and I have done nothing -- Ma, I have done nothing but drive that man to Los Angeles at four in the morning for six months --

DONNA
(quiet)
I know.

JOSH
So what is it? Did she -- was it the money thing? The forty dollars? Is this the forty dollars?

DONNA
I don't know.

JOSH
Did something happen with --
(and here it is; watch him almost reach it)
-- was it something I --

He stops pacing. Somewhere in the sediment of a hundred identical gray mornings, something shifts. The rain. The console. The timer running.

His face changes -- not to certainty. To the exact absence of certainty. Which is so much worse.

JOSH (CONT'D)
(slowly)
The morning with the rain. The follow-up. Was she still on the phone when I --

DONNA
(a long pause; she's done this math already, days ago, alone)
The call was still connected. I don't know if she was still on the line. Sometimes she puts the phone down to help him with the pants.

JOSH
"Sometimes."

DONNA
Sometimes.

JOSH
So she either heard me wish her mother dead, or she was in another room finding pants, and we will never -- 
(he sits down across from her; lands hard)
-- there's no way to ever know.

DONNA
(looking at the tea)
No.

JOSH
And I can't apologize, because if she DIDN'T hear it, the apology IS the confession. I'd be walking a signed statement over to her house.

DONNA
(gently; the whole Coen brothers movie in four words)
So we act normal.

JOSH
(staring at her)
Normal.

DONNA
Thursday's the follow-up on his blood pressure. Four forty-five. We act normal.

A long silence in the little kitchen. The refrigerator hums. Josh puts his face in his hands. Through his fingers, muffled, with no self-pity -- just genuine, awful wonder at the machinery of it:

JOSH
Eleven words. I did everything right for six months and I'm going to lose on eleven words nobody will even ACCUSE me of.

Donna reaches over and pats his arm -- the same arm, the same spot she swatted in the car. Neither of them notices the symmetry. The audience does.

EXT. BERTHA'S HOUSE -- PRE-DAWN -- THURSDAY

The car at the curb. 4:45 exactly. The porch light comes on -- immediately, for the first time in the history of the arrangement. The door opens and Lewis comes out ALONE, dressed, ready, on time.

No Bertha. No stage whisper. No tragedy of the socks.

He gets in the back. Quietly.

LEWIS
Morning.

DONNA
(carefully)
Morning, Lewis. You're bright and early.

LEWIS
(fastening the seatbelt; not meeting anyone's eyes in the mirror)
Bertha got me up. She's been getting me up.

Josh pulls out. Silence in the car. No Dylan. The 118 in the dark.

Josh watches the rearview more than the road. Then, an offering, into the quiet:

JOSH
There's that McDonald's on Los Angeles Avenue. Opens at five.

A pause.

LEWIS
(looking out the window)
I ate.

Two words. The whole cold war in two words. Donna closes her eyes.

The car drives on in the dark, all three of them acting normal, no one saying anything, the space between the front seat and the back seat now approximately four hundred acres across.

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- WAITING ROOM -- MORNING

Lewis checks in at the desk -- he takes the clipboard himself this time, waves off Donna's folder with a polite, terrible little gesture: got it.

Josh stands at the coffee cart. Buys three coffees on autopilot. Looks at the third cup.

There's a veteran in a wheelchair by the window, like always. Different man, same window. Josh carries the coffee over, sets it down.

WHEELCHAIR VETERAN
What's this?

JOSH
Coffee.

WHEELCHAIR VETERAN
Who from?

JOSH
(flat; the bit's still there but the music's gone out of it)
Just take it. It's coffee.

The veteran takes it. Josh walks back to his seat. And here's the scene the whole movie has been building in secret: NOTHING happens. No warmth in the chest. No half-inch drop of the shoulders. He checks his phone. He drinks his own coffee. It's a beverage.

He looks across the waiting room at Lewis, who is filling out his own clipboard, getting the date wrong by a year with nobody to catch it.

Josh looks back at his phone.

HOLD on him: a man doing a kind thing and feeling nothing, which is somehow the saddest shot in a movie that includes cancer.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. DONNA'S KITCHEN -- DAY -- WEEKS LATER

Donna at the table with her phone. She dials. We hear it ring. And ring. Then Bertha's voicemail -- chipper, recorded years ago in better times:

BERTHA (V.O.)
(recording)
You've reached Bertha! Leave a message and God bless!

DONNA
(after the beep; light; the lightness costing her)
Bertha, hi, it's me. Just checking on Thursday -- whether you need us for the podiatry thing. Call me back.

She hangs up. Looks at the phone.

Off her look: this is not the first unreturned message. This is somewhere in the teens.

INT. DONNA'S KITCHEN -- ANOTHER DAY

Donna on the phone, mid-call, standing very still by the window.

DONNA
(into phone)
No -- Carol, I understand, I just -- who's taking him Thursday, then?
(listening)
A service. She hired a service.
(listening; and here it comes, from a friend of a friend, thirdhand, the way these things always arrive)
She said WHAT?

INT. DONNA'S KITCHEN -- CONTINUOUS -- MOMENTS LATER

Josh, summoned from the other room, leans on the doorframe. Donna sits at the table, phone face-down in front of her like something that died.

DONNA
Carol heard it from Bertha's niece. At the graduation party.
(beat)
The story is: we hated them. Her and Lewis and their mother. All along. That's why we "stopped coming around."

JOSH
We stopped --
(he has to walk a small circle)
-- SHE stopped. She stopped answering the PHONE. There's a voicemail box somewhere with nineteen messages from you in it, offering to drive her brother to a podiatrist.

DONNA
That's the story.

JOSH
The story is we hated them. Six months of four-A.M. mornings because of all the hate. I did his cancer research out of spite. You made twenty-one freezer meals with masking-tape labels out of hate.

DONNA
(evenly)
Nobody at that party is going to check.

And that's the line that stops him. Because she's right, and because of how she says it: without surprise. Josh looks at his mother -- at a woman who has known since long before the phone call which way stories travel between houses like Bertha's and kitchens like this one -- and understands that she was braced for some version of this from the beginning. It was never going to end with a thank-you card.

JOSH
(quietly)
You knew she'd do something like this.

DONNA
(standing; collecting the tea cup; done with the subject in the way that means it will never be done)
I knew we weren't friends. I hoped I was wrong.
(at the sink, back to him, almost to herself)
The raise thing told me. You don't say "it would affect our friendship" about forty dollars unless the friendship was always about something else.

She washes the cup. That's the eulogy.

EXT. RALPHS SUPERMARKET -- PARKING LOT -- DAY

And now the movie catches up to itself.

Josh gets out of his car with the reusable bags. Walks toward the entrance. Automatic doors.

INT. RALPHS SUPERMARKET -- THE CEREAL AISLE -- CONTINUOUS

The scene from the cold open, replayed exactly -- same coverage, same fluorescent hum, same instrumental on the PA. Josh with the two identical raisin brans. He looks up. Lewis at the end of the aisle with the coffee bag.

But this time the film stays on it past the cut we made before.

Lewis sets the coffee on the wrong shelf. Turns the cart. Walks away.

And Josh -- instead of standing frozen -- puts down the raisin bran and follows.

INT. RALPHS -- FROZEN AISLE -- CONTINUOUS

Lewis moving down the freezer cases. Josh comes around the endcap ahead of him and stops -- not blocking, just present, ten feet away, hands visible, the way you'd approach anything wounded.

JOSH
Lewis.

LEWIS
(stopping; looking at a freezer door full of waffles)
I got nothing to say to you.

JOSH
Then just listen for eleven seconds. That's all I'm asking. Eleven seconds.

Lewis doesn't leave. Which is the most he can offer, and both of them know it.

JOSH (CONT'D)
Whatever you were told -- and I notice nobody will say it out loud, not to me, not once -- whatever it was: I was there. Four forty-five, every morning, six months. That was real. The McMuffins were real. Track four is real -- I know every word now, I know the live version's better, I know the Rolling Stone review was a hit job. That was me. Whatever the story is now -- the guy in the story isn't the guy who drove the car.

A long silence. Freezer hum. Lewis looks at the waffles. And when he finally speaks, it's not anger -- it's the thing under Lewis, surfacing, the way it always threatened to:

LEWIS
(low)
You know what I got, kid? I got one sister. One. Everybody else is gone or in the ground. And when it gets loud at night -- you remember about loud --
(Josh nods)
-- she's what's left. So when it comes down to her version or your version...
(he finally looks at Josh; and it's terrible, because there's still affection in it, sealed behind glass)
...I can't afford your version. You understand? It's not about true. I can't AFFORD it.

Beat.

LEWIS (CONT'D)
(turning the cart; final; quiet)
You were good to me. I know that part. Both things are just gonna have to be true.

He goes. Josh stands in the frozen aisle among the waffles and the freezer hum, having just lost the argument to the only answer that has no counter: a paranoid man performing the sanest math of his life.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- RALPHS PARKING LOT -- CONTINUOUS

Josh sits behind the wheel. Groceries in the passenger seat. He doesn't start the car.

He takes out his phone. Thumb hovers. Then, to the AI, because it's 2 PM on a Tuesday and there is no one else to say it to:

JOSH
(to the phone)
Hey. Delete the reminder about Lewis's podiatry thing Thursday.

AI VOICE (V.O.)
Done. You also have eleven saved project ideas -- you asked me to remind you to review them this week.

JOSH
(looking out the windshield)
Yeah. What are they.

AI VOICE (V.O.)
A caretaker scheduling app. A VA navigation layer. A meal-prep service for--

JOSH
(listening to the list the way you'd listen to a stranger's eulogy)
Stop.
(beat)
They're all the same idea, aren't they.

AI VOICE (V.O.)
There is significant thematic overlap. Would you like me to consolidate them?

Josh laughs -- once, genuinely, at himself, at the machine's phrasing, at "significant thematic overlap" as the description of his entire soul.

JOSH
No. Leave them.

He starts the car. And here -- quietly, without music -- the realization the whole movie owes us, delivered not as a speech but as a man talking half to a phone and half to a windshield:

JOSH (CONT'D)
It was never about the apps.
(beat)
Six months I told everybody I was helping my mom. Helping Lewis. Being a good guy.
(beat)
I was there because it was the only place I felt like a person. He needed the ride. I needed the four forty-five.
(beat; and this is the important part -- no guilt in it; just the plain fact, examined in daylight)
Both things are just gonna have to be true.

Lewis's own words, handed back. He puts the car in reverse.

INT. VA MEDICAL CENTER -- VOLUNTEER SERVICES OFFICE -- DAY

A small office. A VOLUNTEER COORDINATOR, 50s, unbeatable, behind a desk with a bowl of hard candy.

COORDINATOR
DAV has a volunteer driver network -- vans and personal vehicles. We're always short. It's early mornings, mostly. Real early. Guys come from Lancaster, Ventura, all over, no other way to get here.

JOSH
Early's fine. Early's kind of my thing.

COORDINATOR
(sliding a form across)
Background check, TB test, defensive driving cert. Takes about three weeks. Most people fill this out and I never see them again.

JOSH
(already writing)
You'll see me.

COORDINATOR
(watching him fill it out; conversational)
Whose name goes there is emergency contact.

JOSH
(writing it)
My mother.

COORDINATOR
She drive too?

JOSH
(beat; a small smile at the form)
Better than me.

EXT. A DIFFERENT MODEST HOUSE -- SIMI VALLEY -- PRE-DAWN -- WEEKS LATER

4:45 AM. Dark street. Josh's car idles at the curb of a small stucco house with a wheelchair ramp. The porch light is already on.

The door opens and HECTOR, 70s, Army veteran, rolls himself out and down the ramp with practiced violence, waving off help before any is offered.

HECTOR
(getting himself into the front seat, dismantling into the car piece by piece)
You're early.

JOSH
You were earlier. Light was on.

HECTOR
I don't sleep. Sleeping's how they get you.

JOSH
(pulling out; deadpan)
I heard that about jobs, too.

INT. JOSH'S CAR -- MOVING -- THE 118 WEST -- PRE-DAWN

The old road. The old dark. Hector fiddles with the radio, lands on static, turns it off.

HECTOR
Dialysis, they put you in the chair four hours. You just sit there. You know what I do? I name state capitals. All fifty. Then backwards.

JOSH
Backwards alphabetically or backwards like reversed spelling?

HECTOR
(looking at him with new respect)
...Both. Nobody ever asks that.

They drive. Then Josh, eyes on the road, casual, a man setting down a load so gently it makes no sound:

JOSH
There's a McDonald's up here on the left. Opens at five.

HECTOR
I'm not supposed to have the sodium.

JOSH
Coffee's not sodium.

HECTOR
(considering; the eternal negotiation)
...They got the apple pie this early?

JOSH
(and the answer comes out of him from somewhere deep and healed and permanent)
They always have it.

INT. VA HOSPITAL -- DIALYSIS WAITING AREA -- MORNING

Hector's been taken back. Josh, alone, at the coffee cart. He buys two coffees. Carries one across the waiting room to a WOMAN VETERAN, 60s, in a wheelchair by the window, asleep sitting up.

He sets it down softly on the table beside her. She stirs. Looks at the coffee. Looks at him.

WOMAN VETERAN
What's this?

JOSH
Coffee.

WOMAN VETERAN
Who from?

JOSH
(already walking away; over his shoulder; the old shrug, alive again)
The Marines, probably. They owe you one.

WOMAN VETERAN
(calling after him)
I was Air Force!

JOSH
(not turning around)
Then they REALLY owe you one.

He sits down by the window with his own coffee. And there it is -- small, unannounced, absolutely real: the shoulders come down half an inch. The thing works again. Not because anyone forgave him. Not because the record got corrected -- it never will; somewhere across town there is a graduation party where he hates people, forever. It works because he finally knows what it is and does it anyway, with the meter running and no story attached.

Out the window: the four hundred acres. The chapel. The palms. Somewhere on the far side of all that lawn is a rooftop garden where a man once planned twelve futures.

Josh takes out his phone. Looks at it. Puts it back in his pocket.

He drinks his coffee and waits for Hector, which is the whole job, and enough.

SUPER, SMALL, OVER THE LAST SHOT: "The DAV Transportation Network is staffed entirely by volunteers. They are always short of drivers."

FADE OUT.

THE END

/* PRODUCTION NOTE ON THE ENDING: No reconciliation with Lewis. No comeuppance for Bertha. Nobody ever says the eleven words aloud again, and no one ever confirms she heard them. If a studio note asks for a scene where Bertha gets told off -- the answer is that Bertha getting told off is what a story would do, and this movie is about what actually happens, which is nothing, quietly, forever. The win is the coffee working again. That's the entire third act, and it's enough. */